Taken from AS/NZS 4819:2011, Page 42, Table 2 "Geocode Feature Types and Descriptions"
Point of access to the building
Point at center of building and lying within its bounds (e.g. for U-shaped building).
A point on the road centre-line opposite the centre of the road frontage of an address site
Centre of driveway on address site frontage.
Specific building or property access point for emergency services.
Specific building or property secondary access point for emergency services.
Point on the centre of the address site frontage
A point set back from the centre of the road frontage within an address site.
Access point (centre of) at the road frontage of the property
A point set back from the (centre of the) access point at the road frontage of the property.
Point of centre of parcels making up a property and lying within its boundaries.
Point at centre of unit and lying within its bounds (e.g. for U-shaped unit).
The utility connection point (e.g. box, or underground chamber). Service type to be specified (e.g. water, electricity, gas, telephone).
The utility meter (e.g. box or underground chamber). Service type to be specified (e.g. water, electricity, gas, telephone).

The physical or virtual reference of the geocode. Physical features associated with the address point may include mailbox, driveway, water meter, building. Virtual features are mathematically or geometrically derived spatial reference points such as the centroid of a lot or property or the closest point on a road centreline to property centroid.
This element is to distinguish between a physical address (a geographic place) or virtual address.
